2 task. Estimate the age of the mitochondrial Eve and most recent ancestor of all non-Africans.

Mitochondrial Eve

To estimate the age of the mitochondrial Eve we need to know value of substitutions per site (can be calculated using two taxas and the difference between them) and mutation rate (value that is known from the literature). \(Age = \dfrac{\text{substitutions per site}}{\text{mutation rate}}\) To calculate substitutions per site I used MEGA and Pairwise distance estimation.

Table. Estimates of Evolutionary Divergence between Sequences

In the literature as the observed evolutionary rates range μ is estimated from 4.33 × 10–8 (95% CI 3.90–4.82 × 10–8) mutations per site per year (msy) for the most recent period to 1.91 × 10–8 (95% CI 1.72–2.10 × 10–8) msy for the oldest period (40,160 ± 4658 ya). https://www.nature.com/articles/s41598-021-84583-1

As we need to calculate the age of Eve and the dna was mutating with the increasing speed I would take the average.

\[ Age = 0.00577/(3.12*10^{-8}) = \textbf{184935.9 years} \]

Most recent ancestor of all non-Africans

The same steps can be done to estimate the age of most recent ancestor of all non-Africans. Based on phylogeny tree topology I chose Homo_sapiens_isolate_Y453_haplogroup_L4b2a1 from Yemeni and KT698006.1_Homo_sapiens_isolate_52_Sb_haplogroup_U2e2a4 from Serbia.

According to the tree humans and neanderthals have more resent ancestor then humans and denisovans so the last one separated earlier than neanderthals.
